(44, 2, 30, 10, 23, 2, 2, 'being a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Speech', 'This connection highlights the role of prophecy in both passages. Acts 2:30 refers to a prophet receiving a divine promise, while 2 Samuel 23:2 emphasizes the Spirit of the Lord speaking through the prophet.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 30, 23, 9, 6, 7, 'to sit on his throne', 'Connection of David''s Throne', 'This connection highlights the promise of a ruler from David''s lineage. Both passages emphasize the establishment of a kingdom and throne linked to David.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 30, 42, 1, 31, 33, NULL, 'Connection of David''s Throne', 'This connection highlights the promise of a descendant from David''s lineage who will reign. Both passages emphasize the theme of Jesus being given the throne of David, linking his kingship to God''s covenant with David.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 31, 44, 2, 27, 27, NULL, 'Resurrection Prophecy Connection', 'Both passages emphasize that the soul will not be left in hell and that the flesh will not see corruption. This connection highlights the prophetic nature of the statements regarding the resurrection of Christ.', 'prophecy', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 31, 19, 16, 10, 10, NULL, 'Resurrection and Corruption Connection', 'Both passages emphasize that the soul will not be left in hell and that the Holy One will not see corruption. This connection highlights the prophetic nature of Psalm 16:10 as it is referenced in Acts 2:31 regarding the resurrection of Christ.', 'prophecy', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 31, 44, 13, 35, 35, 'his flesh did see corruption', 'Resurrection and Corruption', 'Both passages emphasize that the Holy One''s flesh did not see corruption, highlighting the significance of Christ''s resurrection. The connection underscores the fulfillment of prophecy regarding the preservation of Christ''s body after death.', 'prophecy', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 31, 60, 1, 11, 12, 'the resurrection of Christ', 'Connection of Prophecy and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the prophetic nature of the sufferings and resurrection of Christ. Both passages emphasize the foretelling of Christ''s sufferings and the subsequent glory, linking the resurrection to the message preached by the apostles.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 32, 44, 3, 15, 15, NULL, 'Resurrection Witnesses Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus and the witnesses to this event. The phrase ''whom God hath raised'' links the two verses, highlighting the continuity of the message about Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 32, 44, 1, 8, 8, 'witnesses', 'Witnesses of Jesus'' Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses. Acts 2:32 states that the apostles are witnesses of Jesus'' resurrection, while Acts 1:8 highlights their mission to be witnesses in various regions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 32, 42, 24, 46, 48, 'we all are witnesses', 'Witnesses of Christ''s Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses to Jesus'' resurrection. Acts 2:32 states, ''we all are witnesses,'' while Luke 24:48 declares, ''ye are witnesses of these things.'' This connection highlights the continuity of the witness theme in the early church.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 32, 43, 15, 27, 27, 'witnesses', 'Witnessing to Jesus'' Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of bearing witness. Acts 2:32 speaks of the apostles as witnesses to Jesus'' resurrection, while John 15:27 emphasizes their role as witnesses due to their close relationship with Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 32, 43, 20, 26, 31, 'this Jesus hath God raised up', 'Resurrection and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus and the importance of belief. Acts 2:32 states that Jesus was raised, while John 20:29 highlights the blessing of those who believe without seeing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 44, 1, 4, 4, NULL, 'Promise of the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the ''promise of the Father.'' Acts 1:4 refers to waiting for this promise, while Acts 2:33 describes its fulfillment through the Holy Ghost being shed forth.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 44, 5, 31, 31, 'by the right hand of God exalted', 'Exaltation and Role of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the exaltation of Christ at God''s right hand. They highlight His role as a source of repentance and forgiveness for Israel.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'the promise of the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Ghost. Acts 2:33 mentions the Holy Ghost being shed forth, while John 14:26 describes the Holy Ghost as the Comforter sent by the Father.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 43, 16, 7, 15, 'the promise of the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Spirit as a Comforter and guide. Acts 2:33 refers to the outpouring of the Holy Spirit, which aligns with John 16:7-15''s promise of the Spirit coming after Jesus'' departure.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 40, 28, 18, 18, 'by the right hand of God', 'Authority and Power of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the exaltation of Jesus and His authority. Acts 2:33 mentions Jesus being ''by the right hand of God,'' which aligns with Matthew 28:18''s declaration of ''All power is given unto me.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 41, 16, 19, 19, 'by the right hand of God exalted', 'Exaltation and Position of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize Christ''s exaltation and position at the right hand of God. Acts 2:33 refers to Him being ''by the right hand of God exalted,'' while Mark 16:19 states He ''sat on the right hand of God.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 33, 48, 3, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of the Holy Spirit Promise', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of the Spirit. Acts 2:33 mentions the Holy Ghost being shed forth, while Galatians 3:14 speaks of receiving the promise of the Spirit through faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 34, 19, 110, 1, 1, 'Sit thou on my right hand', 'David''s Lord and Authority', 'This connection highlights the phrase ''Sit thou on my right hand,'' which appears in both passages. Both verses emphasize the authority given to the Lord over enemies, establishing a link between David''s acknowledgment of divine authority and its fulfillment.', 'quotation', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 34, 40, 22, 42, 45, 'The Lord said unto my Lord', 'David''s Lordship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize David''s reference to the Lord, highlighting the relationship between David and Christ. The phrase ''The Lord said unto my Lord'' is central to understanding this connection.', 'quotation', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 34, 58, 1, 13, 13, 'Sit thou on my right hand', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Sit thou on my right hand,'' indicating a position of authority. This connection highlights the significance of being at God''s right hand, underscoring the exaltation of the one addressed.', 'quotation', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 34, 49, 1, 22, 22, 'Sit thou on my right hand', 'Christ''s Authority and Position', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority, as both passages refer to a figure elevated to a position of power. Acts 2:34 mentions sitting at the right hand, while Ephesians 1:22 emphasizes being head over all things.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 34, 41, 12, 36, 36, 'The Lord said unto my Lord', 'Connection of David''s Lordship', 'Both passages emphasize David''s acknowledgment of a higher authority, as he refers to ''my Lord.'' This connection highlights the theme of divine authority and the role of David in relation to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
